					style and emotionally charged works have left an indelible mark on the
					art world. Van Gogh's art is characterized by his bold and expressive
					brushwork, vibrant colors, and his ability to convey profound emotion
					through his paintings. Despite struggling with mental health issues
					throughout his life, his works, such as "Starry Night" and
					"Sunflowers," continue to captivate viewers with their raw beauty and
					deeply introspective nature.
				</p>
			</Fragment>
			<Fragment slot='2'>
				<p>
					René Magritte was a Belgian surrealist artist known for his
					thought-provoking and dreamlike imagery. Magritte's paintings often
					juxtaposed ordinary objects in unexpected and mysterious ways,
					challenging viewers' perception and the conventions of reality. He
					explored themes of identity, perception, and the relationship between
					language and image. With his meticulous attention to detail and his
					ability to create a sense of ambiguity, Magritte's works, like "The
					Son of Man" and "The Treachery of Images," continue to captivate and
					intrigue art enthusiasts worldwide.
				</p>
			</Fragment>
			<Fragment slot='3'>
				<p>
					Edward Hopper was an American realist painter known for his evocative
					depictions of urban and rural scenes. Hopper's art often portrayed
					solitary figures, empty streets, and quiet moments, reflecting a sense
					of isolation and introspection. His use of light and shadow, along
					with his keen observation of everyday life, created a sense of mood
					and narrative within his paintings. Hopper's iconic works, such as
					"Nighthawks" and "Morning Sun," captured the essence of modern
					American life, and his unique visual language continues to resonate
					with viewers, inviting them to contemplate the complexities of human
					experience.
				</p>
			</Fragment>
